003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hUiginn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Uiginn</i>’, a byname meaning ‘viking, sea-rover’ (from Old Norse <i>víkingr</i>). Compare   McGuigan  .","English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of <b>Higgin</b>, itself either a Lancashire variant of <b>Huggin</b> (from a pet form of   Hugh  ), or a variant of   Hickin   (from a pet form of   Richard  ), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. See   Hick   and compare   Higson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Higgens","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Higgins  ."]},{"name":"McGuigan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam, Mairead.","Irish (northern): perhaps an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Uiginn</b> ‘son of the viking’ (see   Higgins   1).","Irish (northern): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Guagáin</b>, a shortened form of <b>Mag Eochagáin</b>, son of <i>Eochagán</i>, a diminutive of <i>Eochaidh</i> ‘horseman’. Compare   Geoghegan  ."]},{"name":"Haggins","meanings":["Scottish variant of Irish   Higgins  ."]},{"name":"Heggins","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Higgins   1."]},{"name":"Kiggins","meanings":["Irish (Galway and Mayo) and Manx: shortened Anglicized form (with English excrescent <i>-s</i>) of Gaelic <b>Mag Uiginn</b> ‘son of the Viking’ (see   Higgins  )."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":8,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":81,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Hugh Higins Ist was born in 1374, in Shropshire, England. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Hugh Higgins 1st. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1374–":"1374–Surnud","1376–Female":"1376–Surnud","1395–1417":"1395–1417","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","Abt 1395":"umbes 1395","1455":"1455","1376":"1376","1374":"1374","1395":"1395","1382":"1382","1417":"1417","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","of Wolverton, Shropshire, Englan